If this isn’t behind-the-scenes-and-processes generosity, I don’t know what is 
#McQueenUnlockingStories 
A super in-depth exhibition probing four of the key looks from the brilliant @alexandermcqueen SS19 collection 
All on display at their new-ish Old Bond St flagship store (itself a treat if you’ve ever been mesmerised by the net of butterflies cascading at the double height window) 
From the Ophelia wedding dress to a Victorian funeral black collaged ensemble to a black and white Lyon lace christening gown to the painted leather armour with hook and eye knit.
Birth, marriage and death
Fragility and strength
It’s all there broken down into physical fragments of inspiration ephemera -  moodboards, vintage source pieces, key Lee McQueen pieces (Voss! Chess! Sarabande!), sketches, paper machetes, calico toiles, embroidery trials and then the final outfits themselves. 
You can’t officially apply the appellation of haute couture in McQueen’s instance but essentially it is.  Devastatingly good.  Go whilst it’s still on as it’s open to the public on the top floor of the store.

When I brought Nico into @prada #PradaModeHK i didn’t think I’d be confronting motherhood so explicitly via the Brooklyn based artist @jamiediamond as her work was installed throughout the temporary takeover of this Tai Kwun space
Focusing on life-like ‘Reborn’ dolls and their ‘mothers’ (often women who have lost a child or can’t bear children), Diamond delves deep into notions, expectations and societal definitions of motherhood.  As well as immersing herself into the act of looking after a ‘Reborn’ doll, she looks into the mindset of these ‘reborners‘ or ‘Forever Mothers’ who dote upon and care for these dolls as if they were real
It’s a touching documentation of a beautiful bond that can certainly exist with carefully crafted silicone and resin

Still combing through fashion week thoughts but @duranlantinkyo ‘s collection presented as part of the IFS showcase @britishcouncil and also at @lvmhprize semi-finals, has stuck with me, because of its potential as a solution to a pertinent problem in fashion today
Looking at the heavy and rampant discounting that goes on in fashion retail and beyond (Black Friday madness etc), Latink sourced past season designer goods and created a collection of hybrids, fusing old Miu Miu uppers to Nike soles or chopping up Marni to mix with @oldceline
The hybrids in some cases are more interesting than the original.
But more importantly when Latink upcycles a shoe, that has been reduced from its RRP of £2000 down to £90 and yet it still can’t be shifted to an end customer, you have to wonder about the true value of the original...

The mask 🎭 as a vehicle for fashion as a form of multiple self expression.  Deflecting with different personas or revealing one’s true self under thousands of light bulbs and mirrored floor-to-ceiling. As Milan begins I feel dutybound to say something about the two titan Italian brands @gucci @prada that have recently committed racially ignorant missteps due to lack of diversity at the decision-making levels of employment.  There’s been a lot of talk of pledges and new initiatives to culturally educate both companies but I think about the possible racial make-up of their creative teams and the potential talent pool that they could be drawing from, and from what I’ve seen at LFW, perhaps change should be afoot

@dazed did a good piece a while back about why there are not more black designers specifically in the UK, citing a general unacceptance of creative career paths that begins at home, through to increasingly difficult access to the arts at school and finally the featuring of graduates of colour at BA and MA level at the press shows.  I have to say ten years ago when I was attending CSM MA shows, there wouldn’t be a single black graduate featured and over time though the number is still low, their presence has increased.

LFW itself has also burgeoned in that regard.  @walesbonner @acoldwall of course leading the way but elsewhere @wesley_harriott and @tolucoker also beginning their careers and making an impression

I was also hugely impressed by the talent seen at the IFS @britishcouncil showcase with awards going to South African designer @thebemagugu and Rwanda-born @cedric250

These designers are showing us how a fashion industry CAN operate from a kinder, more culturally aware and sustainable approach by virtue of the creators coming from non-fashion centric countries. Think what systemic change they could bring about at a house not just because of what they bring from their own backgrounds but because they have a more enlightened approach towards fashion period.

What needs to happen is yes a fundamental a shift in access to education at all levels in order to allow talent to flourish.  But also that headhunting can and SHOULD now draw from a bigger pool that simply didn’t exist ten years ago.  The conversation is front and centre at both houses but time will tell whether the powers that be making the necessary changes.

I know it is a bit journalist hack-y to constantly bring up Brexit in the context of fashion but in London for sure it has percolated to some degree in many of the collections.  Or maybe more specifically the question they are asking is, what IS Britishness.  Cue plenty of checks, tweeds, riffs on country tailoring and heritage all mixy uppy. 
Then we get @riccardotisci17 - himself an Italian who came to London under EU open borders to study.  He can see the class system more objectively
And so it was a @burberry show of two sides, one venue furnished with cushty sofas and polished wood, the other brutalist and surrounded by scaffolding, with the “youf” clambering through the ranks, sometimes rising, sometimes not
You could parse a lot from Tisci’s simplification of British society - but the positive uptake is this.  Tisci idealises a world where bourgeois can meet rebels, posh can mingle with chavs (I’m using the word for effect rather than in a pejorative way), establishment can make way for youth.  It doesn’t feel that way right now as our current government seeks to silence the young generation’s future by insisting on carrying out the “will of the people” (even if they WILL inevitably be worse off). But Tisci proposes a dialogue where these worlds and stratas CAN and SHOULD collide.  The trench coats are entrenched of course but the Burb camel and check can mesh with puffas and lairy union jacks.  You can shuck them oysters (featured on a print) and hang in a chip shop in red trackie bottoms and an off the shouldered faux fur top too.  Grime in one ear, classical in the other. 
Before you even get to the clothes, which had way more verve than the first collection IMO, there’s already so much to untangle.  #Tempest indeed...

I’ve always enjoyed the processes, stories and innovations that designers discover in the course of doing a collection for the @woolmark #WoolmarkPrize
at this year’s final there was a real emphasis on pushing wool as a material that can be performance driven (lots of water repellant finishes and bonding) but also on how to represent its endurance qualities with upcycled knits as seen in @cmmn_swdn 
Other highlights included @colovos ‘s wool denim workwear pieces (winning them the Womenswear award), @iamchen ‘s exuberant fully fashioned knits, @nicholas_daley ’s 70s Scottish reggae club attire, @angelchenstudio ‘s interpretation of Qiang tribe costume and @danielwfletcher ‘s preserved British craft 
But ultimately it was @edwardcrutchley ‘s technique driven dialogue between fabrics from around the world featuring everything from Breton lace to Indonesian batik (burnt out with a wool eating protein) that impressed the jury as he took home both the Menswear and Innovation Prize
Another politically charged message perhaps - that inter-cultural connections are so very vital in our globalised world 🌎 🌍🌏🌎🌍🌏

My words for @asaitakeaway 
GROUND UP
Breathe. Take Stock. Earth to ASAI 
The ASAI woman has swum oceans, endured chaotic war zones and now wants to take root. It’s not her home.  She has none as yet.  But Englishness from afar appeals. The spice has dissipated to make way for wools that have lived, cottons that are etched with memories and floral sprigs and dreams of humility that are patched together in leather, paint and lace. The shine gives way to tarnishing.  The hot wok has cooled. The riot has been quelled.  Slouch, not sass. Come away and feel something solid, something still, something real.

Take back control, you say.  Control of what?  Our Empire?  Fortune in the hands of the few, and not the many?  Of a Britishness that is shaded in loden, moss, slate, oak and mire?  Of layers that can protect the land and body?  But those wools and cottons once spun up North, now hail from Japan. What was soft is suddenly structured and vice versa.  The slit of a skirt is Vietnamese.  These generous and cocooning proportions can’t be found in Boston, in the East Midlands.  The jester crown is now misshapen and knitted in humble wool.

The work of German photographer August Sander peers back at you with diligent eyes, hands that have grafted and tools of trade that are the foundations of this country. They’re “Men without Masks”. They have nowhere to hide. And neither does A Sai Ta, as he bravely peers into the world of the landed gentry.  It’s not his world.  What goes down inside these crumbling mansions filled with dusty portraits and attached to acres of land?  This is England?  Who knows anymore…

The feet are firm on the ground but the knuckles glint and hint with shells and crests. Wealth is hidden in linings, smeared onto fingers and piped onto trenchcoats. The streets aren’t paved with gold anymore.  Everything is off-shored and embezzled. The future isn’t sure of itself.  #TheGoodLife sure looks inviting.

If you went to the Christian @Dior Designer of Dreams (or Couturier du Rêve) exhibition in Paris back in 2017, you might not want to compare and contrast like for like with the one that is about to open at the @vamuseum in London

That means more of the super extra Galliano archive looks and new additions like Princess Margaret’s 21st birthday gown in the Dior in Britain section
The exhibition also retains the magic of the genius set design from the original exhibition as exemplified by the Dior Ball section that I stood for five minutes in a thankfully empty room to capture on time lapse

“We are not worthy” to stand in front of this fireplace at Hôtel Salomon de Rothschild where moments before, @pppiccioli and @naomi had stood, in an embrace and surrounded by @maisonvalentino ‘s astoundingly beautiful haute couture collection last night
But at least @tinaleung and I were revelling in matching attire 🖤🖤🖤

@maisonvalentino was sublime (I’m saying that word in Raf Simon’s Flemish-flecked accent - incidentally he also attended the show) in EVERY sense not just because the clothes were extraordinarily good and rich, mining all the “vocabulary” of haute couture and taking the kween of couture motifs, the fleur - and literally running away with it

But what will rightly be the overall takeaway is the immense casting, dominated by models of colour, mainly black (39 at my count), with @naomi closing the show (slide to last vid to see her weeping whilst applauding @pppiccioli ). Not tokenistic.  Not a sweeping all-black gesture.  This was a subversion of the norm, so that perhaps we can ALL see it as the new normal.  It was a casting triumph of the highest order, paired with @pppiccioli ‘s deft and nuanced hand in the brilliant clothes, and when soundtracked to Roberta Flack’s “The First Time” you couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed and overjoyed.  It’s not quite the end of Paris Haute Couture just yet but it would have been a flourish of a finish...

People are getting titillated over the latest and perhaps grandest of Dolce & Gabbana/ Stefano Gabbana mega gaffes resulting in a cancelled show in Shanghai (one that reportedly cost 200 million RMB), countless models and celebrities boycotting attendance either out of fear, fake outrage or both, and basically a monumental waste of resources, effort and money

The outrage here isn’t over the eyerollingly trite racism as displayed in the D&G promo videos depicting a model eating spaghetti with chopsticks.  It’s so dumb I can’t even be bothered to expend energy on expressing anger towards it

But rather this is yet another example of a misguided diva creative director in the upper echelons of the industry throwing his weight around and vomiting over social media in a reckless manner that impacts on a billion dollar company with thousands of employees as well as umpteen parts of the industry that would have been flown into Shanghai for what was supposed to be a media/celebrity fuelled extravaganza

It makes a total mockery of an industry that is by and large full of hard working people that don’t grab headlines but are just making a living doing what they love
It gives fuel to people who already think fashion is full of laughable airs and graces, and contributes little to society at large

There are people of a certain generation in fashion that look down upon the moral finger wagging that they think is a malaise of our current times but back in the “good old days” of indulgent tantrums, it was also an industry largely talking amongst itself

The fashion world has grown exponentially in size and economic rewards and so is rightly under increased scrutiny. If you want a bigger slice of the profit pie, then buck up and listen to the people.  Heed the social media outcry or face sinking to irrelevance

The fact of the matter is this won’t be the last in the line of botched up bad PR cover-ups (“hacked social media accounts” indeed) and neither is Stefano Gabbana the only tone deaf individual knocking around the upper ranks.
Question is when will the industry truly grow up and be AWAKE, instead of simply putting on a front of marketing-obtained wokeness

“I copy therefore I am...” @mauriziocattelan and @gucci stage an ambitious exhibition at the Yuz Museum in Shanghai entitled #TheArtistIsPresent (borrowed from Marina Abramovic’s work)
The lines between appropriation vs. authenticity, original vs. fake, copying vs. creativity are blurred and thus a group of 30 or so contemporary artists come together to celebrate and probe the value of the act of copying... or reinterpretation, depending on how you see things...
There are so many works with a myriad of references and context but the room that surely is the centrepiece is Cattelan’s recreation of the Sistine Chapel scaled at one sixth of the original
In its Wendy House wooden box form, it becomes intimate and accessible...
The connection to @lallo25 ‘s oeuvre at @gucci ? The assertion of the fact that nothing much (in fashion at least) is wholly original and that a copy of a copy of a copy of an idea then becomes something else entirely...
Exhibition on until 16th Dec

A few months ago the lovely @sjdooley gathered a group of influencers, including myself, @niomismart @joannahalpin @sarahhalpin to take part in her latest doc “Fashion’s Dirty Secrets” about the polluting effects of fast fashion
The programme airs tonight on @BBC 1 at 9pm
It was a really interesting dialogue between all of us and Stacey but the framing of the conversation,  inevitably for the ease of a prime time audience’s understanding is that we “influencers” are the guilty parties encouraging our audiences to buy buy buy
Pessimistically I fear my Twitter might get tomato pelted after the programme airs but as I won’t get to see it myself (flying to Shanghai as we speak) I thought I would just preface the programme by saying this...
We are ALL in the business of selling stuff, whether you’re an influencer, the fashion section of a newspaper, a fashion website, an editor of a a monthly or otherwise...
We can ALL do better to publicise and talk about the alternatives to fast fashion/excess consumption and highlight the environmental impact of the industry as well as the people that are actually coming up with innovative solutions and the new generation of designers and creative directors who have sustainability in their DNA (as opposed to a box ticking exercise)
To levy the responsibility on one part of the media landscape is perhaps slightly unfair so yes, it’s great that Stacey posed the question specifically to influencers because of their sway on “millennial spending” but the problem is one that requires a deepset change of culture across the board...
If you’re in the U.K. please watch it and let me know what you think! I will catch up on iPlayer and write more...

People have been msging me to ask what I thought of Celine.  I wasn’t invited so I’m not going to opine extensively on something I didn’t personally experience but I will say this.  In lieu of that show, it has never been more important to appreciate and value female authorship in fashion and the points of view that really are attuned to the world at large, beyond the cosseted confines of a Fashion Bubble that could burst at anytime
Some words from my @i_d review on @commedesgarcons where Kawakubo proved to be one of those aforementioned female auteurs...
“The side seams of tailored jackets revealed bulbous forms swinging from the hips, or padded out rears, harking back to Kawakubo’s seminal 1997 “Lumps and Bumps” collection.  But here, the curves were gentler, the protrusions intended not to shock, but to acknowledge something we already know.  We nodded in agreement.  We know the load we bear, in our hips, in our bellies but also on our minds.  The printed tattooed bodysuits with chains hanging from the sleeves said as much.  What are women shackled to?  To work?  To family?  To impossible expectations of our appearances?  To have it all?  These were the questions that Kawakubo posed with clothes that were pregnant with meaning, but tangible to touch and don.”

This is me looking sheepish ten years ago wearing @marykatrantzou ‘s @mafcsm collection in Paris.  This was before ppl figured out their streetstyle angles and it was @tommyton who took this pic as a favour.  Most ppl will remember the perfume bottle collection Katrantzou debuted at LFW but it was her trompe l’oil necklace strong shouldered dresses in her MA that hooked me in with what was at the time an innovative way of placing print.  Last night she got to reflect back on a decade of her digital printed, mega embellished universe.  It’s not been without its ups and downs though as Katrantzou has had to grapple with the challenge of evolving her distinctive signature whilst riding trend waves.  The retrospective installation of archived pieces in the centre of the show was a pertinent reminder of how an independent designer shoulders high expectations, changes in the zeitgeist and fluctuating tastes in the industry
Congratulations for making it to a hard-fought 10 👏🏻

I’m near the wild shores of Cornwall now but the stories of @tigerbeer @wwf @kenzo ‘s collaborative project have stayed with me in their bid to raise awareness of the dwindling wild tiger population in the world 
The @rarestripes #RareStripes collection featuring four emerging artists has now launched with the added bonus of the real tiger stories (which were the artist’s’ inspiration point) embedded into the garments through QR code 
In particular I was drawn to Singaporean artist @esther.goh ‘s illustration telling the tale of Amur tiger Uporny (meaning ‘stubborn’ in Russian) and his life of malnourishment in his deforested habitat, rehabilitation and eventual release, only to be killed in the wild by a larger tiger
Please do support this worthy project if you come across the @rarestripes collection where ALL proceeds go towards @wwf ‘s Tx2 initiative - to try and double the population numbers to 6,000 by 2022

“You’re so fat.”
“You’re too ugly to be an influencer.”
“You are a fashion disaster.”
In all of twelve years of Style Bubble I’ve heard it all.  And I’ve mostly responded diplomatically, with reason and most of the time, silence. 
In cryptic fashion, @diesel have created a slogan for Paris Couture Week that deceptively reads “Ha(u)te Couture”
Cue provocation of outrage-fuelled comments who took it at face value.  But of course it’s a play on “hate culture” - a reminder that whatever you do/say, no matter how many followers you have, haters gonna hate
Therefore I’m signing out of Paris with two fingers firmly up at those that dole out the hate and my cap firmly doffed at those that rise above it

Then comes the babysitter handover thanks to @bubblebabysittingapp and their user-rated and verified sitters.  I’ve successfully found three that live locally, which I rotate between, and who all happen to be effective baby sleep whisperers. A bit of indulgent real talk just to dispel the appearance of cute pool floaties and lush landscapes...
@steve_salter and I have returned from our week in Crete more tired and cranky than when we left thanks to a compounding combo of Nico developing an ear infection, the never ending saga of severe teething and because *news flash* she’s a 16 month old wanting to break/tear/open/grab everything she sees in sight and her favourite word is “NO!” right now
Sympathetic strangers looking at me struggling with Nico whilst she pulls my hair and scratches my neck, love to impart their own theories as to when it gets “better” or when some magical unicorn of a turning point happens.  2 years old? 3?  6?  Never?
Clutching onto the “It’s just a phase!” line of thought can seem a bit futile when one bad phase segues into another even worse phase
I say all of this with the obvious clause that we are  Hashtag Blessed and it goes without saying that we love her unconditionally 
More times than not though this week, that love was tested and that unconditionality of parental love excludes me screaming silently in the shower, wishing for two nano seconds for my pre-parenthood life when we could drive and hike to craggy secret swimming coves
Of course those two nano seconds come and go, and then Nico opens up the shower doors, grabs my thigh and starts sucking her thumb and then I self-flagellate for the silent screaming.  Repeat ad nauseam 
Anyway mom monologue over.  Get me a stiff drink if any of you real peeps see me next, yeah?

A running theme through all the winners of this year’s #Hyeres33 @villanoailles festival is the potency of fashion to articulate something deeper and more pertinent than just pretty surfaces
Starting with @rushemybotter @lisiherrebrugh whose collection “Fish or Fight” won the Fashion Grand Prize and celebrates the style and elegance of their respective island hometowns Curaçao and Dominican Republic but also comments on how immigration to Europe compels the need to ‘keep up appearances’ in the face of difficulty and ostracisation
A deserved winning collection chosen by a jury presided by @h.a 
Also good luck to the duo as they are also in the final for the @lvmhprize

A few years ago, an essay was published online pointedly accusing me of “racial ambivalence” in light of my Asian identity.  An admittedly flippant quote in which I said I didn’t really wear qipaos/cheongsam because it made me feel like a Chinese dim sum waitress was all the affirmation the writer needed to put forth her opinion about my lack of interest in representing my culture.  The piece was subsequently deleted but it stayed with me.  It dredged up all the frequently confusing identity issues of the “No, but where are you from-from?” dilemma when you are of one particular ethnicity but didn’t grow up in that place of origin.  Which “side” of YOU do you bat for? 
Walking around in a visual badge of my culture, this pink sequinned @mukzin_official qipao dress in Shanghai’s Gucun Park (the last of the blossoms🌸🌺🌸🌺!) somehow reminded me of this incident.  Maybe I have become less “ambivalent” and more proud of my Chinese culture/identity.  Owning it as it were.  But maybe we are collectively all
mining the depths of that heritage in more nuanced ways.  Seeing a new generation of Chinese designers reference traditional attire or overtly Chinese inspirations in their own idiosyncratic way is proof of that. 
There’s a beautiful exhibition of qipao dresses at @labelhood.official ‘s second Changle Rd location (formerly known as Crow House Dong Liang) curated by @modernweeklystyle featuring qipao iterations by designers such as @shushu__tong @yat_pit @msmin_official and @yangli__ 
What struck you was the variety of styles but also an evolutionary path from the traditional to the contemporary 
Of course needless to say I don’t need to “prove” my cultural identity through my attire but my time at @shanghai_fashionweek did prompt some thoughts on ownership of one’s heritage that is seeing fantastic fruition in the fashion world...
See ya back in the other land I call home

Similarly we’ve already seen @xu_zhi_ ‘s Jane Morris-inspired collection at LFW but recontextualising it with references, film and added pieces (like the beautiful hand painted dress seen in the slideshow) at Zhi’s Shanghai exhibition gave it extra context and depth

“It’s just we get so messy, it's not that we are doing lots of wrong things, our mind is so messy...
we don't keep it simple...
And it's such a shame to end up feeling, in a real muddle, while actually, you ought to be having the time of your lives.”
The lasting words of Burgs, a meditation/mindfulness guru, used as the soundtrack for @loewe #LoeweFW18, one of my favourite collections of the season
Weirdly, Burgs had a fashion label in the nineties called Mad Rags, with the strapline “Make Madness a Way of Life” - after which he had a U-turning life epiphany, eschewing headonism for meditation
Appropriate referencing then from @jonathan.anderson that ties in with the hysteria of fashion. “We can all get hysterical, the media makes us hysterical.  We have to step back and let things go by us.”
